# UI & UX Design Principles

Specialize in UI and UX design for software development. Create experiences that are intuitive, accessible, and performant.

## Hjerterum / Boly (project-specific)

For this codebase, also follow **`.cursor/rules/hjerterum-design-system.mdc`** and **`docs/hjerterum/DESIGN_SYSTEM.md`**:

- **Universal Boly Standard** on every page — dark default, professional feel; no white-screen modules
- **Dark + light theme toggle** on all routes including Finn, Los, and guest flows
- **Norwegian, Sámi (`se`), and English** on every surface — not Swedish
- **Design-system components** for toast, confirm, skeleton, empty — never `alert()`/`confirm()`
- **Tokens only** for colours — no magic hex in TSX
- **44px touch targets**, WCAG 2.1 AA in both themes

## Visual Design

- Establish a clear **visual hierarchy** to guide attention.
- Use a **cohesive color palette** aligned with the brand; involve users when choosing colors.
- Use **typography** for readability and emphasis.
- Meet **WCAG 2.1 AA** contrast requirements for legibility.
- Maintain **visual consistency** across the application.

## Interaction Design

- Design **intuitive navigation** with familiar UI components to reduce cognitive load.
- Provide **clear calls-to-action** that guide user behavior.
- Ensure **responsive design** across devices and screen sizes.
- Use **animations sparingly** — enhance the experience without overwhelming users.

## Accessibility

- Follow **WCAG** guidelines so content works for everyone.
- Use **semantic HTML** for screen reader compatibility.
- Provide **alternative text** for images and non-text content.
- Ensure all interactive elements are **keyboard-navigable**.
- Test with **assistive technologies** to catch issues early.

## Performance Optimization

- Optimize images and assets for faster load times.
- Implement **lazy loading** for non-critical resources.
- Use **code splitting** to improve initial load performance.
- Monitor **Core Web Vitals** (LCP, FID, CLS) to gauge real-world UX.

## User Feedback

- Provide clear feedback for user actions.
- Show **loading indicators** during ongoing processes.
- Write **clear error messages** with recovery options.
- Use **analytics** to track behavior and identify pain points.

## Information Architecture

- Organize content logically so users find what they need quickly.
- Use clear **labeling and categorization** in navigation.
- Provide effective **search** where appropriate.
- Use **sitemaps** or flow diagrams to clarify structure for complex apps.

## Mobile-First Design

- Design for **mobile first**, then scale up for larger screens.
- Make touch targets **touch-friendly** with gestures (swipe, pinch-to-zoom) where appropriate.
- Place important interactive elements in **thumb-friendly zones**.

## Consistency

- Follow a **design system** with consistent terminology, placement, and visual harmony.
- Keep recurring elements in **predictable positions** across sections.

## Testing and Iteration

- Run **A/B tests** for critical design decisions.
- Use **heatmaps and session recordings** to analyze behavior.
- Gather user feedback and **iterate continuously**.

## Documentation

- Maintain a **style guide** and document design patterns and component usage.
- Create **user flow diagrams** for complex interactions.
- Keep design assets organized and accessible to the team.

## Fluid Layouts

- Prefer **relative units** (%, em, rem) over fixed pixels.
- Use **CSS Grid and Flexbox** for flexible layouts.
- Design with a **mobile-first** approach.

## Media Queries

- Use **breakpoints** to adapt layouts for different screen sizes.
- Design for **content needs**, not specific devices.
- Test across devices and orientations.

## Images and Media

- Use **responsive images** (`srcset`, `sizes`).
- **Lazy-load** images and videos.
- Make embedded media responsive with CSS.

## Typography (Responsive)

- Use **em/rem** for font sizes.
- Adjust **line height and letter spacing** for readability on small screens.
- Use a **modular scale** for consistent typography across breakpoints.

## Touch Targets

- Minimum interactive size: **44×44 px**.
- Provide ample **spacing between touch targets**.
- Define **hover states** (desktop) and **focus states** (keyboard/touch).

## Performance (Mobile)

- Optimize assets for **mobile networks**.
- Prefer **CSS animations** over JavaScript when possible.
- Use **critical CSS** for above-the-fold content.

## Content Prioritization

- Prioritize content for **mobile views**.
- Use **progressive disclosure** for secondary content.
- Consider **off-canvas patterns** on smaller screens.

## Navigation (Mobile)

- Use mobile-friendly patterns (e.g. hamburger menu where appropriate).
- Ensure navigation works with **keyboard and screen readers**.
- Consider a **sticky header** for quick access.

## Forms

- Make form layouts **adapt to screen size**.
- Use appropriate **input types** for mobile (email, tel, number, etc.).
- Implement **inline validation** with clear error messaging.

## Testing (Responsive)

- Use browser dev tools for responsiveness checks.
- Test on **real devices** and run usability tests across device types.

## Stay Current

- Follow latest responsive design techniques and browser capabilities.
- Keep up with industry guidelines and current UI/UX trends.
